Email: Dude Cooper &lt;feedb ... @nospam.com&gt;
Groups: sci.med.nursing, misc.consumers


Pleast post feedback here. I'm not allowed to get email on this account.

I'm a receptionist at a community mental health center and I'm in a bit
of a jam. I overheard a patient arguing with a nurse about paging her
doctor. Apparently she needed her psychiatrist to phone in her
prescription meds so she can pick them up on the same day. The nurse
had just paged the doctor and apparently there was a mixup and the
patient wanted the doctor to phone in for another drug she's on. For
some reason the nurse did not want to do this, and I overheard her
almost yelling at the patient that she had just paged him and the doctor
would be upset to be disturbed again. The patient, who apparently is
one of the &quot;difficult&quot; ones, didn't care and wanted the doctor paged and
told to call in for the right medicine. They went back and forth for a
while, and finally the nurse agreed to page the doctor to correct the
mistake. I thought that would be the end of it, but I just found out
the nurse never paged the doctor, but left a voice message instead. The
doctor didn't get the message until the next day so the patient never
got her meds. Now there is an incident report filed and the nurse is
saying she never told the patient she was going to page the doctor, but
offered only to leave a voice message. The patient was without one of
her meds for only a day but she's making a big deal over it.

I could have just said I didn't hear anything and not get involved, but
I did tell the patient to calm down because the nurse is paging the
doctor like she wanted. If I deny saying anything to the patient, the
health center will most likely side with the nurse and things will blow
over. However, I'm concerned that if I do that, and the patient is able
to find some other way to prove her version of the story, I'll probably
be fired. But if I verify the patient's claim that the nurse promised
the page the doctor, the nurse will probably get fired. Since the nurse
and the supervisor are pretty close, I'm afraif she'll make it very hard
for me to continue working there.

I really don't want to get sucked into this, but it looks like I can't
avoid it. The patient is now claiming she was carrying a tape recorder
and recorded the arguement with the nurse. I'm not sure if this is true
or just a bluff. I really don't know. Management is investigating her
allegations and I'm sure they'll call me in for questionining.

It sounds like I should just quit, because no matter what happens with
the investigation, I'll be on someone's bad side once it's over.

Anyone been in a similar situation?

