I cannot attest to what Mike is saying but a couple of posters did make a
good point about presenting an emotional story.

When I am dealing with either a nurse or a patient who is not in immediate
danger, I always suggest waiting a day or two before they put their account
of activity into writing. A 'just the facts, ma'am' approach eliminates the
recipient of the information from getting the idea that personal likes or
dislikes has anything to do with the original complaint.

As a receptionist in an outpatient clinic, the OP should not present
clinical judgments. Rather, she should present the facts and let others
determine if the behavior was clinically warranted. However, it seems from
the OP that the nurse lied to the patient about paging the doc and instead
left a voice message which was not retrieved until the following day. Lying
to a patient is never acceptable.

